&#8232;We live in a world inundated with media and saturated with images. What might be reported through television, documentary films, or magazines was once presented via illustrated texts and prints or else commemorated in public murals or statues. This course will follow the emergence of modern media - culminating in photography, film, and digital media - in an increasingly public and democratic sphere of art. Social changes in courts and cities, especially in the wake of the Industrial and French Revolutions, resulted from increasing capitalism and democracy. Artists had to adjust to new roles, media, and means of support. This course will introduce students from diverse backgrounds to visual media in culture and society, providing both critical and historical tools for visual literacy in the modern world. &#8232;&#8232;
Students found the course to be a strong overview of art history but were split on opinions regarding the structure of the course, which in Spring 2009 was taught thematically as opposed to chronologically. While some thought this style was interesting and made the material easier to follow, a majority found the class to be too complex for an introductory level course and argued that this structure left “students with no background in art history at a disadvantage.” Overall, students felt the class was “way too difficult for an introductory art history course” and one art history minor commented, “this course discourages people from pursuing art history.” Students expressed that “paper topics, exams and trips to the art museum were highly disorganized and put together at the very last minute,” which tended to detract from the learning experience. &#8232;&#8232;
Students appreciated Professor Poggi’s communication skills and tended to enjoy her lectures. Many expressed that Professor Poggi was “very good at relaying main ideas of a lecture” and one student declared that she is “one of the best faculty in the Art History department.” &#8232;
&#8232;This class fulfills the Arts & Letters Sector requirement and there are no prerequisites for this course. Students tended to encourage others with prior art history experience to take this course, and believed that beginners may have a difficult time with the material based on the structure of this class.

